at the portico of the sāʿidah clan -- tWhat ʿUmar said about the members of the shura -- tAbū bakr's designation of ʿumar as his successor -- tThe oath of fealty pledged to abū bakr -- tThe expedition of dhāt al-salāsil and the story of ʿalī and muʿāwiyah -- tThe story of al-ḥajjāj ibn ʿilāṭ -- tThe dispute between ʿalī and Al-ʿabbās -- tThe story of Abū luʾluʾah, ʿumar's assassin -- tThe story of the Shura -- tThe expeditions to al-qādisiyyah and elsewhere -- tThe marriage of fāṭimah -- tNotes -- tGlossary of names, places, and terms -- tGenealogical table of the Quraysh of mecca -- tBibliography -- tFurther reading -- tIndex -- tAbout the nyu abu dhabi institute 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Expeditions is one of theoldest biographies of the Prophet Muhammad to survive into the modern era. Itsprimary author, Ma'mar ibn Rashid (714-770 AD/96-153 AH), was a prominentscholar from Basra in southern Iraq who was revered for his learning inprophetic traditions, Islamic law, and the interpretation of the Qur'an. Thisfascinating foundational seminal work contains stories handed down by Ma'mar tohis most prominent pupil, 'Abd al-Razzaq of Sana'a, relating Muhammad's earlylife and prophetic career as well as the adventures and tribulations of hisearliest followers during their conquest of the Near East.Editedfrom a sole surviving manuscript, the Arabic text offers numerous improvedreadings over those of previous editions, including detailed notes on thetext's transmission and variants as found in later works. This new translation,which renders the original into readable, modern English for the first time, isaccompanied by numerous annotations elucidating the cultural, religious andhistorical contexts of the events and individuals described within its pages.TheExpeditions representsan important testimony to the earliest Muslims' memory of the lives of Muhammadand his companions, and is an indispensable text for gaining insight into thehistorical biography of both the Prophet and the rise of the Islamic empire.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 08. Jun 2020) 0aIslamxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Middle East / General.2bisacsh1 aAnthony, Sean W., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHaleem, M.A.S. Abdel40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814729298423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780814729298.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK